		"body": "\r\nFixes #9606\r\n\r\n## Problem\r\nWhen importing notes from an ENEX file (Evernote export), notes that are intended to remain in HTML format were being imported with `markup_language` set to Markdown.\r\n\r\nAs a result, Joplin attempted to render HTML content as Markdown, which could lead to incorrect formatting and inconsistent rendering of imported notes.\r\n\r\nThis happens because the `markup_language` field was not determined based on the selected `outputFormat` during the ENEX import process.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\nThis PR updates the ENEX import logic in `packages/lib/import-enex.ts` so that the `markup_language` is assigned according to the chosen `outputFormat`.\r\n\r\n- If the output format is `html`, the note is stored with  \r\n  `MarkupToHtml.MARKUP_LANGUAGE_HTML`.\r\n- Otherwise, the note is stored with  \r\n  `MarkupToHtml.MARKUP_LANGUAGE_MARKDOWN`.\r\n\r\nThis ensures that notes imported from ENEX preserve the correct markup language and are rendered appropriately.\r\n\r\nThe change is minimal and limited to the markup assignment logic without modifying the existing conversion behaviour.\r\n\r\n## Test Plan\r\n\r\nManual testing was performed using the following steps:\r\n\r\n1. Export notes from Evernote as an ENEX file containing HTML-formatted notes.\r\n2. Import the ENEX file into Joplin.\r\n3. Verify that imported notes with HTML content have `markup_language` set to HTML.\r\n4. Confirm that the notes render correctly without Markdown misinterpretation.\r\n5. Import ENEX notes using Markdown output format and verify that Markdown rendering continues to work as expected.\r\n\r\nAdditionally:\r\n- Verified that importing notes without HTML content behaves as before.\r\n- Confirmed that other note properties (title, resources, tasks, etc.) remain unaffected.\r\n\r\nThis change affects the shared import logic and therefore applies to all platforms (Desktop, Mobile, CLI).",
